[src:mkdocs/comparison-of-documentation-generators] The following tables compare general and technical information for a number of documentation generators.
[src:mkdocs/comparison-of-documentation-generators] Please see the individual products' articles for further information.
[src:mkdocs/comparison-of-documentation-generators] Unless otherwise specified in footnotes, comparisons are based on the stable versions without any add-ons, extensions or external programs.
[src:mkdocs/comparison-of-documentation-generators] Note that many of the generators listed are no longer maintained.
[src:mkdocs/comparison-of-documentation-generators] Basic general information about the generators, including: creator or company, license, and price.
[src:mkdocs/comparison-of-documentation-generators] The output formats the generators can write.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Guide to all available configuration settings.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Project settings are configured by default using a YAML configuration file in the project directory named `mkdocs.yml`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] You can specify another path for it by using the `-f`/`--config-file` option (see `mkdocs build --help`).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] At a minimum, this configuration file must contain the `site_name`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This is a **required setting**, and should be a string that is used as the main title for the project documentation.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] When rendering the theme this setting will be passed as the `site_name` context variable.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This will add a `link` tag with the `canonical` URL to the `head` section of each HTML page.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If the 'root' of the MkDocs site will be within a subdirectory of a domain, be sure to include that subdirectory in the setting (`https://example.com/foo/`).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This setting is also used for `mkdocs serve`: the server will be mounted onto a path taken from the path component of the URL, e.g.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] `some/page.md` will be served from `http://127.0.0.1:8000/foo/some/page/` to mimic the expected remote layout.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] When set, provides a link to your repository (GitHub, Bitbucket, GitLab, ...) on each page.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] When set, provides the name for the link to your repository on each page.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The path from the base `repo_url` to the docs directory when directly viewing a page, accounting for specifics of the repository host (e.g.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] GitHub, Bitbucket, etc), the branch, and the docs directory itself.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] MkDocs concatenates `repo_url` and `edit_uri`, and appends the input path of the page.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] When set, and if your theme supports it, provides a link directly to the page in your source repository.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This makes it easier to find and edit the source for the page.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If `repo_url` is not set, this option is ignored.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] On some themes, setting this option may cause an edit link to be used in place of a repository link.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The `edit_uri` supports query ('?') and fragment ('#') characters.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For repository hosts that use a query or a fragment to access the files, the `edit_uri` might be set as follows.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For other repository hosts, simply specify the relative path to the docs directory.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For more flexibility, see edit_uri_template below.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] On a few known hosts (specifically GitHub, Bitbucket and GitLab), the `edit_uri` is derived from the 'repo_url' and does not need to be set manually.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Simply defining a `repo_url` will automatically populate the `edit_uri` configs setting.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For example, for a GitHub- or GitLab-hosted repository, the `edit_uri` would be automatically set as `edit/master/docs/` (Note the `edit` path and `master` branch).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For a Bitbucket-hosted repository, the equivalent `edit_uri` would be automatically set as `src/default/docs/` (note the `src` path and `default` branch).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] To use a different URI than the default (for example a different branch), simply set the `edit_uri` to your desired string.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If you do not want any "edit URL link" displayed on your pages, then set `edit_uri` to an empty string to disable the automatic setting.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] On GitHub and GitLab, the default "edit" path (`edit/master/docs/`) opens the page in the online editor.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This functionality requires that the user have and be logged in to a GitHub/GitLab account.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Otherwise, the user will be redirected to a login/signup page.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Alternatively, use the "blob" path (`blob/master/docs/`) to open a read-only view, which supports anonymous access.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] (they are also mutually exclusive -- don't specify both).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Starting from here, you can change the positioning or formatting of the path, in case the default behavior of appending the path isn't enough.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This will add a meta tag to the generated HTML header.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Set the copyright information to be included in the documentation by the theme.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Set the remote branch to commit to when using `gh-deploy` to deploy to GitHub Pages.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This option can be overridden by a command line option in `gh-deploy`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Set the remote name to push to when using `gh-deploy` to deploy to GitHub Pages.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This setting is used to determine the format and layout of the global navigation for the site.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] All paths in the navigation configuration must be relative to the `docs_dir` configuration option.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] See the section on configuring pages and navigation for a more detailed breakdown, including how to create sub-sections.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Navigation items may also include links to external sites.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] While titles are optional for internal links, they are required for external links.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] An external link may be a full URL or a relative URL.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Any path which is not found in the files is assumed to be an external link.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] See the section about Meta-Data on how MkDocs determines the page title of a document.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] In the above example, the first two items point to local files while the third points to an external site.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, sometimes the MkDocs site is hosted in a subdirectory of a project's site and you may want to link to other parts of the same site without including the full domain.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] In that case, you may use an appropriate relative URL.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] In the above example, two different styles of external links are used.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] First, note that the `site_url` indicates that the MkDocs site is hosted in the `/foo/` subdirectory of the domain.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Therefore, the `Home` navigation item is a relative link that steps up one level to the server root and effectively points to `https://example.com/`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The `Bug Tracker` item uses an absolute path from the server root and effectively points to `https://example.com/bugs/`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Of course, the `User Guide` points to a local MkDocs page.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This config no longer applies the "drafts" functionality for `mkdocs serve`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If you have draft documents that you want available in "serve" and not "build", replace `exclude_docs` with the new `draft_docs` config option.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This config defines patterns of files (under `docs_dir`) to not be picked up into the built site.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This follows the .gitignore pattern format.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] So, in order to really start this config fresh, you'd need to specify a negated version of these entries first.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This config defines patterns of files (under `docs_dir`) to be treated as a draft.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Draft files are available during `mkdocs serve` and include a "DRAFT" mark but will not be included in the build.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] To prevent this effect and make "serve" behave the same as "build", you can run `mkdocs serve --clean`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If the `nav` config is not specified at all, pages specified in this config will now be excluded from the inferred navigation.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If you want to include some docs into the site but intentionally exclude them from the nav, normally MkDocs warns about this.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Adding such patterns of files (relative to `docs_dir`) into the `not_in_nav` config will prevent such warnings.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] As the previous option, this follows the .gitignore pattern format.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Adding a given file to `exclude_docs` takes precedence over and implies `not_in_nav`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Configure the strictness of MkDocs' diagnostic messages when validating links to documents.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This is a tree of configs, and for each one the value can be one of the three: `warn`, `info`, `ignore`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Which cause a logging message of the corresponding severity to be produced.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The `warn` level is, of course, intended for use with `mkdocs build --strict` (where it becomes an error), which you can employ in continuous testing.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The config `validation.links.absolute_links` additionally has a special value `relative_to_docs`, for validation of absolute links.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] (Note: you shouldn't copy this whole example, because it only duplicates the defaults.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The defaults of some of the behaviors already differ from MkDocs 1.4 and below - they were ignored before.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Note how in the above examples we omitted the 'nav' and 'links' keys.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Here `absolute_links:` means setting both `nav: absolute_links:` and `links: absolute_links:`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If you set the setting `validation.links.absolute_links` to the new value `relative_to_docs`, all Markdown links starting with `/` will be understood as being relative to the `docs_dir` root.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The links will then be validated for correctness according to all the other rules that were already working for relative links in prior versions of MkDocs.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For the HTML output, these links will still be turned relative so that the site still works reliably.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] "dir1/foo.md") can link to the document "dir2/bar.md" as `[link](/dir2/bar.md)`, in addition to the previously only correct way `[link](../dir2/bar.md)`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The default is still to just skip the link.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Sets the theme and theme specific configuration of your documentation site.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] May be either a string or a set of key/value pairs.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If a string, it must be the string name of a known installed theme.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For a list of available themes visit Choosing Your Theme.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The string name of a known installed theme.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] A code representing the language of your site.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This can either be a relative directory, in which case it is resolved relative to the directory containing your configuration file or it can be an absolute directory path from the root of your local file system.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] See Customizing Your Theme for details if you would like to tweak an existing theme.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] See the Theme Developer Guide if you would like to build your own theme from the ground up.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] A list of templates to render as static pages.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The templates must be located in either the theme's template directory or in the `custom_dir` defined in the theme configuration.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Any additional keywords supported by the theme can also be defined.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] See the documentation for the theme you are using for details.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The directory containing the documentation source markdown files.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This can either be a relative directory, in which case it is resolved relative to the directory containing your configuration file, or it can be an absolute directory path from the root of your local file system.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The directory where the output HTML and other files are created.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If you are using source code control you will normally want to ensure that your *build output* files are not committed into the repository, and only keep the *source* files under version control.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If you're using another source code control tool, you'll want to check its documentation on how to ignore specific directories.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Set a list of CSS files (relative to `docs_dir`) to be included by the theme, typically as `<link>` tags.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Set a list of JavaScript files in your `docs_dir` to be included by the theme, as `<script>` tags.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Older versions of MkDocs supported only a plain list of strings, but now several additional config keys are available: `type`, `async`, `defer`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Only the plain string variant detects the `.mjs` extension and adds `type="module"`, otherwise `type: module` must be written out regardless of extension.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] `*.js` and `*.css` files, just like any other type of file, are always copied from `docs_dir` into the site's deployed copy, regardless if they're linked to the pages via the above configs or not.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Set a list of templates in your `docs_dir` to be built by MkDocs.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] To see more about writing templates for MkDocs read the documentation about custom themes and specifically the section about the available variables to templates.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] A set of key-value pairs, where the values can be any valid YAML construct, that will be passed to the template.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This allows for great flexibility when creating custom themes.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Determines additional directories to watch when running `mkdocs serve`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Allows a custom default to be set without the need to pass it through the `-w`/`--watch` option every time the `mkdocs serve` command is called.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The paths provided via the configuration file are relative to the configuration file.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The paths provided via the `-w`/`--watch` CLI parameters are not.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This setting controls the directory structure of the generated documentation, and thereby the URL format used for linking to pages.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The following tables demonstrate how the directory structure and URLs used on the site differ when setting `use_directory_urls` to `true` or `false`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This setting is needed when the documentation is hosted on systems that can't access the file `X/index.html` when given the URL `X`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] When set to `false`, no additional `X` directory is created, and the file is simply stored as `X.html`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Links are created that point directly to the target *file* rather than a target *directory*.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The default style of `use_directory_urls: true` creates more user friendly URLs, and is usually what you'll want to use.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Set to `true` to halt processing when a warning is raised.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Set to `false` to print a warning and continue processing.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This is also available as a command line flag: `--strict`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Determines the address used when running `mkdocs serve`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Allows a custom default to be set without the need to pass it through the `--dev-addr` option every time the `mkdocs serve` command is called.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] MkDocs uses the Python Markdown library to translate Markdown files into HTML.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Python Markdown supports a variety of extensions that customize how pages are formatted.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This setting lets you enable a list of extensions beyond the ones that MkDocs uses by default (`meta`, `toc`, `tables`, and `fenced_code`).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Some extensions provide configuration options of their own.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If you would like to set any configuration options, then you can nest a key/value mapping (`option_name: option value`) of any options that a given extension supports.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] See the documentation for the extension you are using to determine what options they support.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Note that a colon (`:`) must follow the extension name (`toc`) and then on a new line the option name and value must be indented and separated by a colon.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Add an additional item to the list for each extension.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] To dynamically configure the extensions, you can get the config values from environment variables or obtain paths of the currently rendered Markdown file or the overall MkDocs site.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] In the above examples, each extension is a list item (starts with a `-`).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] As an alternative, key/value pairs can be used instead.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, in that case an empty value must be provided for extensions for which no options are defined.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This alternative syntax is required if you intend to override some options via inheritance.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The Python-Markdown documentation provides a list of extensions which are available out-of-the-box.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For a list of configuration options available for a given extension, see the documentation for that extension.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] You may also install and use various third party extensions (Python-Markdown wiki, MkDocs project catalog).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Consult the documentation provided by those extensions for installation instructions and available configuration options.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] A list of paths to Python scripts (relative to `mkdocs.yml`) that are loaded and used as plugin instances.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This does not enable any new abilities compared to plugins, it only simplifies one-off usages, as these don't need to be *installed* like plugins do.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Note that for `mkdocs serve` the hook module will *not* be reloaded on each build.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] You might have seen this feature in the mkdocs-simple-hooks plugin.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If a hook file has a file `foo.py` adjacent to it, it can use the normal Python syntax `import foo` to access its functions.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] In older versions of MkDocs, a workaround was necessary to make this work - adding the path to `sys.path`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] A list of plugins (with optional configuration settings) to use when building the site.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] See the Plugins documentation for full details.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However MkDocs also ensures that each plugin has the `enabled` boolean option.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] In the above examples, each plugin is a list item (starts with a `-`).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, in that case an empty value must be provided for plugins for which no options are defined.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] A search plugin is provided by default with MkDocs which uses lunr.js as a search engine.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] A regular expression which matches the characters used as word separators when building the index.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] By default whitespace and the hyphen (`-`) are used.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] An integer value that defines the minimum length for a search query.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] By default searches shorter than 3 chars in length are ignored as search result quality with short search terms are poor.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, for some use cases (such as documentation about Message Queues which might generate searches for 'MQ') it may be preferable to set a shorter limit.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] A list of languages to use when building the search index as identified by their ISO 639-1 language codes.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] You may contribute additional languages.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] While search does support using multiple languages together, it is best not to add additional languages unless you really need them.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Each additional language adds significant bandwidth requirements and uses more browser resources.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Generally, it is best to keep each instance of MkDocs to a single language.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Lunr Languages does not currently include support for Chinese or other Asian languages.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, some users have reported decent results using Japanese.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Optionally generates a pre-built index of all pages, which provides some performance improvements for larger sites.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Before enabling, confirm that the theme you are using explicitly supports using a prebuilt index (the builtin themes do).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This option requires that Node.js be installed and the command `node` be on the system path.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If the call to `node` fails for any reason, a warning is issued and the build continues uninterrupted.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] You may use the `--strict` flag when building to cause such a failure to raise an error instead.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] On smaller sites, using a pre-built index is not recommended as it creates a significant increase is bandwidth requirements with little to no noticeable improvement to your users.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, for larger sites (hundreds of pages), the bandwidth increase is relatively small and your users will notice a significant improvement in search performance.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Configures what strategy the search indexer will use when building the index for your pages.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This property is particularly useful if your project is large in scale, and the index takes up an enormous amount of disk space.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] In most cases, the value of a configuration option is set directly in the configuration file.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, as an option, the value of a configuration option may be set to the value of an environment variable using the `!ENV` tag.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] If the environment variable is not defined, then the configuration setting would be assigned a `null` (or `None` in Python) value.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] A default value can be defined as the last value in a list.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Multiple fallback variables can be used as well.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Note that the last value is not an environment variable, but must be a value to use as a default if none of the specified environment variables are defined.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Simple types defined within an environment variable such as string, bool, integer, float, datestamp and null are parsed as if they were defined directly in the YAML file, which means that the value will be converted to the appropriate type.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, complex types such as lists and key/value pairs cannot be defined within a single environment variable.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For more details, see the pyyaml_env_tag project.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Some Markdown extensions can benefit from knowing the path of the Markdown file that's currently being processed, or just the root path of the current site.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For that, the special tag `!relative` can be used in most contexts within the config file, though the only known usecases are within `markdown_extensions`.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] This allows the pymdownx.snippets extension to include files relative to the current Markdown file, which without this tag it would have no way of knowing.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Even for the default case, any extension's base path is technically the *current working directory* although the assumption is that it's the *directory of mkdocs.yml*.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Generally, a single file would hold the entire configuration for a site.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, some organizations may maintain multiple sites which all share a common configuration across them.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Rather than maintaining separate configurations for each, the common configuration options can be defined in a parent configuration file which each site's primary configuration file inherits.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] To define the parent for a configuration file, set the `INHERIT` (all caps) key to the path of the parent file.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The path must be relative to the location of the primary file.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For configuration options to be merged with a parent configuration, those options must be defined as key/value pairs.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Specifically, the markdown_extensions and plugins options must use the alternative syntax which does not use list items (lines which start with `-`).
[src:mkdocs/configuration] When running `mkdocs build`, the file at `foo/mkdocs.yml` would be passed in as the configuration file.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] MkDocs will then parse that file, retrieve and parse the parent file `base.yml` and deep merge the two.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Deep merging allows you to add and/or override various values in your primary configuration file.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] For example, suppose for one site you wanted to add support for definition lists, use a different symbol for permalinks, and define a different separator.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Notice that the `admonition` extension was retained from the parent configuration, the `def_list` extension was added, the value of `toc.permalink` was replaced, and the value of `toc.separator` was added.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] You can replace or merge the value of any key.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, any non-key is always replaced.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Therefore, you cannot append items to a list.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] As the nav configuration is made up of nested lists, this means that you cannot merge navigation items.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Of course, you can replace the entire `nav` configuration with a new one.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] However, it is generally expected that the entire navigation would be defined in the primary configuration file for a project.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] As a reminder, all path based configuration options must be relative to the primary configuration file and MkDocs does not alter the paths when merging.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] Therefore, defining paths in a parent file which is inherited by multiple different sites may not work as expected.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] It is generally best to define path based options in the primary configuration file only.
[src:mkdocs/configuration] The inheritance can also be used as a quick way to override keys on the command line - by using stdin as the config file.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] Material for MkDocs is a powerful documentation framework on top of MkDocs, a static site generator for project documentation.1 If you're familiar with Python, you can install Material for MkDocs with `pip`, the Python package manager.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] Material for MkDocs is published as a Python package and can be installed with `pip`, ideally by using a virtual environment.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] This will automatically install compatible versions of all dependencies: MkDocs, Markdown, Pygments and Python Markdown Extensions.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] Material for MkDocs always strives to support the latest versions, so there's no need to install those packages separately.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] If you don't have prior experience with Python, we recommend reading Using Python's pip to Manage Your Projects' Dependencies, which is a really good introduction on the mechanics of Python package management and helps you troubleshoot if you run into errors.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] The official Docker image is a great way to get up and running in a few minutes, as it comes with all dependencies pre-installed.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] The `mkdocs` executable is provided as an entry point and `serve` is the default command.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] If you're not familiar with Docker don't worry, we have you covered in the following sections.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] The Docker container is intended for local previewing purposes only and is not suitable for deployment.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] This is because the web server used by MkDocs for live previews is not designed for production use and may have security vulnerabilities.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] Material for MkDocs only bundles selected plugins in order to keep the size of the official image small.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] If the plugin you want to use is not included, you can add them easily.
[src:mkdocs/getting-started] The new image will have additional packages installed and can be used exactly like the official image.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] The initial description of Markdown contained ambiguities and raised unanswered questions, causing implementations to both intentionally and accidentally diverge from the original version.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] This was addressed in 2014 when long-standing Markdown contributors released CommonMark, an unambiguous specification and test suite for Markdown.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Markdown was inspired by pre-existing conventions for marking up plain text in email and usenet posts, such as the earlier markup languages setext (c.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] In 2002, Aaron Swartz created atx and referred to it as "the true structured text format".
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Gruber created the Markdown language in 2004 with Swartz as his "sounding board".
[src:mkdocs/markdown] The goal of the language was to enable people "to write using an easy-to-read and easy-to-write plain text format, optionally convert it to structurally valid XHTML (or HTML)".
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Gruber wrote a Perl script, `Markdown.pl`, which converts marked-up text input to valid, well-formed XHTML or HTML, encoding angle brackets (`<`, `>`) and ampersands (`&`), which would be misinterpreted as special characters in those languages.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] It can take the role of a standalone script, a plugin for Blosxom or Movable Type, or of a text filter for BBEdit.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] As Markdown's popularity grew rapidly, many Markdown implementations appeared, driven mostly by the need for additional features such as tables, footnotes, definition lists, and Markdown inside HTML blocks.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] The behavior of some of these diverged from the reference implementation, as Markdown was only characterised by an informal specification and a Perl implementation for conversion to HTML.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] At the same time, a number of ambiguities in the informal specification had attracted attention.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] These issues spurred the creation of tools such as Babelmark to compare the output of various implementations, and an effort by some developers of Markdown parsers for standardization.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] However, Gruber has argued that complete standardization would be a mistake: "Different sites (and people) have different needs.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Gruber avoided using curly braces in Markdown to unofficially reserve them for implementation-specific extensions.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] In 2012, a group of people, including Jeff Atwood and John MacFarlane, launched what Atwood characterised as a standardization effort.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] A community website now aims to "document various tools and resources available to document authors and developers, as well as implementors of the various Markdown implementations".
[src:mkdocs/markdown] In September 2014, Gruber objected to the usage of "Markdown" in the name of this effort and it was rebranded as "CommonMark".
[src:mkdocs/markdown] CommonMark.org published several versions of a specification, reference implementation, test suite, and "[plans] to announce a finalized 1.0 spec and test suite in 2019".
[src:mkdocs/markdown] A finalized 1.0 spec has not been released, as major issues still remain unsolved.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Nonetheless, several websites and projects have adopted CommonMark, including Codeberg, Discourse, GitHub, GitLab, Reddit, Qt, Stack Exchange (Stack Overflow), and Swift.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Websites like Bitbucket, Diaspora, Discord, GitHub, OpenStreetMap, Reddit, SourceForge and Stack Exchange use variants of Markdown to make discussions between users easier.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Depending on implementation, basic inline HTML tags may be supported.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Italic text may be implemented by `_underscores_` or `*single-asterisks*`.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Many platforms implement spoiler formatting that hides text until hovered, clicked or tapped.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] The most common markup is ||spoiler|| used by Discord, Telegram, various Matrix clients, now defunct Guilded, a forum called Flarum, a NodeBB plugin, the imageboard engine JSChan and possibly more.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] GitHub had been using its own variant of Markdown since as early as 2009, which added support for additional formatting such as tables and nesting block content inside list elements, as well as GitHub-specific features such as auto-linking references to commits, issues, usernames, etc.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] In 2017, GitHub released a formal specification of its GitHub Flavored Markdown (GFM) that is based on CommonMark.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] It is a strict superset of CommonMark, following its specification exactly except for tables, strikethrough, autolinks and task lists, which GFM adds as extensions.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Accordingly, GitHub also changed the parser used on their sites, which required that some documents be changed.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] For instance, GFM now requires that the hash symbol that creates a heading be separated from the heading text by a space character.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Markdown Extra is a lightweight markup language based on Markdown implemented in PHP (originally), Python and Ruby.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Markdown Extra is supported in some content management systems such as Drupal, Grav (CMS), Textpattern CMS and TYPO3.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Implementations of Markdown are available for over a dozen programming languages; in addition, many applications, platforms and frameworks support Markdown.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] For example, Markdown plugins exist for every major blogging platform.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] While Markdown is a minimal markup language and is read and edited with a normal text editor, there are specially designed editors that preview the files with styles, which are available for all major platforms.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Many general-purpose text and code editors have syntax highlighting plugins for Markdown built into them or available as optional download.
[src:mkdocs/markdown] Editors may feature a side-by-side preview window or render the code directly in a WYSIWYG fashion.
[src:mkdocs/read-the-docs] The site was created in 2010 by Eric Holscher, Bobby Grace, and Charles Leifer.
[src:mkdocs/read-the-docs] On March 9, 2011, the Python Software Foundation Board awarded a grant of US$840 to the Read the Docs project for one year of hosting fees.
[src:mkdocs/read-the-docs] On November 13, 2017, the Linux Mint project announced that they were moving their documentation to Read the Docs.
[src:mkdocs/read-the-docs] In 2020, Read the Docs received a $200,000 grant from the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative.
[src:mkdocs/read-the-docs] For 2021, Read the Docs reported 700 million page views and 196 million unique visitors.
[src:mkdocs/read-the-docs] In 2013, a "Write the Docs" conference for Read the Docs users was launched, which has since turned into a generic software-documentation community.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] How to layout and write your Markdown source files.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Your documentation source should be written as regular Markdown files (see Writing with Markdown below), and placed in the documentation directory.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] By default, this directory will be named `docs` and will exist at the top level of your project, alongside the `mkdocs.yml` configuration file.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] By convention your project homepage should be named `index.md` (see Index pages below for details).
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Any of the following file extensions may be used for your Markdown source files: `markdown`, `mdown`, `mkdn`, `mkd`, `md`.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] All Markdown files included in your documentation directory will be rendered in the built site regardless of any settings.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Files and directories with names which begin with a dot (for example: `.foo.md` or `.bar/baz.md`) are ignored by MkDocs.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] This can be overridden with the `exclude_docs` config.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The file layout you use determines the URLs that are used for the generated pages.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] You can also include your Markdown files in nested directories if that better suits your documentation layout.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Any files which are not identified as Markdown files (by their file extension) within the documentation directory are copied by MkDocs to the built site unaltered.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] See how to link to images and media below for details.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] When a directory is requested, by default, most web servers will return an index file (usually named `index.html`) contained within that directory if one exists.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] For that reason, the homepage in all of the examples above has been named `index.md`, which MkDocs will render to `index.html` when building the site.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Many repository hosting sites provide special treatment for README files by displaying the contents of the README file when browsing the contents of a directory.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Therefore, MkDocs will allow you to name your index pages as `README.md` instead of `index.md`.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] In that way, when users are browsing your source code, the repository host can display the index page of that directory as it is a README file.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] However, when MkDocs renders your site, the file will be renamed to `index.html` so that the server will serve it as a proper index file.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] If both an `index.md` file and a `README.md` file are found in the same directory, then the `index.md` file is used and the `README.md` file is ignored.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The nav configuration setting in your `mkdocs.yml` file defines which pages are included in the global site navigation menu as well as the structure of that menu.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] If not provided, the navigation will be automatically created by discovering all the Markdown files in the documentation directory.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] An automatically created navigation configuration will always be sorted alphanumerically by file name (except that index files will always be listed first within a sub-section).
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] You will need to manually define your navigation configuration if you would like your navigation menu sorted differently.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] If that option is set to the default value, `docs`, the source files for the above configuration would be located at `docs/index.md` and `docs/about.md`.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The above example will result in two navigation items being created at the top level and with their titles inferred from the contents of the Markdown file or, if no title is defined within the file, of the file name.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] To override the title in the `nav` setting add a title right before the filename.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Note that if a title is defined for a page in the navigation, that title will be used throughout the site for that page and will override any title defined within the page itself.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Navigation sub-sections can be created by listing related pages together under a section title.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] With the above configuration we have three top level items: "Home", "User Guide" and "About." "Home" is a link to the homepage for the site.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Note that a section cannot have a page assigned to it.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Sections are only containers for child pages and sub-sections.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] You may nest sections as deeply as you like.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] However, be careful that you don't make it too difficult for your users to navigate through the site navigation by over-complicating the nesting.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] While sections may mirror your directory structure, they do not have to.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Any pages not listed in your navigation configuration will still be rendered and included with the built site, however, they will not be linked from the global navigation and will not be included in the `previous` and `next` links.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Such pages will be "hidden" unless linked to directly.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] MkDocs pages must be authored in Markdown, a lightweight markup language which results in easy-to-read, easy-to-write plain text documents that can be converted to valid HTML documents in a predictable manner.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] MkDocs uses the Python-Markdown library to render Markdown documents to HTML.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Python-Markdown is almost completely compliant with the reference implementation, although there are a few very minor differences.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] In addition to the base Markdown syntax which is common across all Markdown implementations, MkDocs includes support for extending the Markdown syntax with Python-Markdown extensions.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] See the MkDocs' markdown_extensions configuration setting for details on how to enable extensions.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] MkDocs includes some extensions by default, which are highlighted below.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] MkDocs allows you to interlink your documentation by using regular Markdown links.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] However, there are a few additional benefits to formatting those links specifically for MkDocs as outlined below.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] When linking between pages in the documentation you can simply use the regular Markdown linking syntax, including the *relative path* to the Markdown document you wish to link to.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] When the MkDocs build runs, these Markdown links will automatically be transformed into an HTML hyperlink to the appropriate HTML page.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Using absolute paths with links is not officially supported.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Relative paths are adjusted by MkDocs to ensure they are always relative to the page.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] This means that your links using absolute paths might work fine in your local environment but they might break once you deploy them to your production server.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] If the target documentation file is in another directory you'll need to make sure to include any relative directory path in the link.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The toc extension is used by MkDocs to generate an ID for every header in your Markdown documents.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] You can use that ID to link to a section within a target document by using an anchor link.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The generated HTML will correctly transform the path portion of the link, and leave the anchor portion intact.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Note that IDs are created from the text of a header.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] All text is converted to lowercase and any disallowed characters, including white-space, are converted to dashes.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Consecutive dashes are then reduced to a single dash.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Note that if you would like to define multiple of the above settings, you must do so under a single `toc` entry in the `markdown_extensions` configuration option.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] As well as the Markdown source files, you can also include other file types in your documentation, which will be copied across when generating your documentation site.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] These might include images and other media.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Your image will now be embedded when you build the documentation, and should also be previewed if you're working on the documentation with a Markdown editor.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Markdown allows document authors to fall back to raw HTML when the Markdown syntax does not meets the author's needs.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] MkDocs does not limit Markdown in this regard.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] However, as all raw HTML is ignored by the Markdown parser, MkDocs is not able to validate or convert links contained in raw HTML.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] When including internal links within raw HTML, you will need to manually format the link appropriately for the rendered document.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] MkDocs includes support for both YAML and MultiMarkdown style meta-data (often called front-matter).
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Meta-data consists of a series of keywords and values defined at the beginning of a Markdown document, which are stripped from the document prior to it being processing by Python-Markdown.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The key/value pairs are passed by MkDocs to the page template.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Therefore, if a theme includes support, the values of any keys can be displayed on the page or used to control the page rendering.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] See your theme's documentation for information about which keys may be supported, if any.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] In addition to displaying information in a template, MkDocs includes support for a few predefined meta-data keys which can alter the behavior of MkDocs for that specific page.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] A title defined in the `title` meta-data key of a document.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] A level 1 Markdown header on the first line of the document body.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] YAML style meta-data consists of YAML key/value pairs wrapped in YAML style delimiters to mark the start and/or end of the meta-data.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The first line of a document must be `---`.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The meta-data ends at the first line containing an end deliminator (either `---` or `...`).
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The content between the delimiters is parsed as YAML.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Therefore, in the above example, the values of `title`, `summary` and `some_url` are strings, the value of `authors` is a list of strings and the value of `date` is a `datetime.date` object.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Note that the YAML keys are case sensitive and MkDocs expects keys to be all lowercase.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The top level of the YAML must be a collection of key/value pairs, which results in a Python `dict` being returned.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] If any other type is returned or the YAML parser encounters an error, then MkDocs does not recognize the section as meta-data, the page's `meta` attribute will be empty, and the section is not removed from the document.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] MultiMarkdown style meta-data uses a format first introduced by the MultiMarkdown project.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The keywords are case-insensitive and may consist of letters, numbers, underscores and dashes and must end with a colon.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The values consist of anything following the colon on the line and may even be blank.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] If a line is indented by 4 or more spaces, that line is assumed to be an additional line of the value for the previous keyword.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] A keyword may have as many lines as desired.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] All lines are joined into a single string.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The first blank line ends all meta-data for the document.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Therefore, the first line of a document must not be blank.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] MkDocs does not support YAML style delimiters (`---` or `...`) for MultiMarkdown style meta-data.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] In fact, MkDocs relies on the the presence or absence of the delimiters to determine whether YAML style meta-data or MultiMarkdown style meta-data is being used.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] If the delimiters are detected, but the content between the delimiters is not valid YAML meta-data, MkDocs does not attempt to parse the content as MultiMarkdown style meta-data.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The tables extension adds a basic table syntax to Markdown which is popular across multiple implementations.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The syntax is rather simple and is generally only useful for simple tabular data.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Note that table cells cannot contain any block level elements and cannot contain multiple lines of text.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] They can, however, include inline Markdown as defined in Markdown's syntax rules.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Additionally, a table must be surrounded by blank lines.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] There must be a blank line before and after the table.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] The fenced code blocks extension adds an alternate method of defining code blocks without indentation.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Note that fenced code blocks can not be indented.
[src:mkdocs/writing-your-docs] Therefore, they cannot be nested inside list items, blockquotes, etc.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] MkDocs is a **fast**, **simple** and **downright gorgeous** static site generator that's geared towards building project documentation.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] Documentation source files are written in Markdown, and configured with a single YAML configuration file.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] Start by reading the introductory tutorial, then check the User Guide for more information.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] There's a stack of good looking themes available for MkDocs.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] Choose between the built in themes: mkdocs and readthedocs, select one of the third-party themes (on the MkDocs Themes wiki page as well as the MkDocs Catalog), or build your own.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] Get your project documentation looking just the way you want it by customizing your theme and/or installing some plugins.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] Modify Markdown's behavior with Markdown extensions.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] Many configuration options are available.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] The built-in dev-server allows you to preview your documentation as you're writing it.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] It will even auto-reload and refresh your browser whenever you save your changes.
[src:mkdocs/www-mkdocs-org] MkDocs builds completely static HTML sites that you can host on GitHub Pages, Amazon S3, or anywhere else you choose.
